<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Crater theory over missing Beagle<br>
Monday, December 29, 2003 Posted: 7:25 AM EST (1225 GMT)<br>
LONDON, England (AP) -- Scientists have ruled out two possible explanations for their inability to pick up signals from Europe's Beagle 2 Mars probe and discovered another -- a large crater where the vessel was supposed to land. <br>
<br>
The European team has received no transmissions from the craft, which was supposed to touch down on the distant planet on Christmas Day to begin its search for Martian life. <br>
<br>
NASA's orbiting Mars Odyssey has passed five times over the spot where scientists hope Beagle landed, without picking up a signal. The latest attempt, between 0741 and 0901 GMT Monday, failed to pick up a bark from Beagle. <br>
<br>
Chief Beagle scientist Colin Pillinger said at a news conference that the team had received a new, detailed picture of the area where they believe the Beagle landed. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>excerpted, see link f</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Internet wags are having a lot of fun with this one:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I have my own &quot;crater theory&quot;: Judge Crater got up Christmas morning, found the thing on his lawn, and called Martian Disposal Services to take it away.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It's payback to the Brits for the Martian army being massacred by the common cold back in 1898, per H.G. Wells. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(Note: <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>War of the Worlds</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> was set in 1901, though this is mentioned only once in the text.)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The Martians saw the Union Jack decal and (being fuzzy on the dimensions of the human body) decided that Robert Fisk was inside. They promptly beat it to a pulp.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A> at: 12/30/03 4:18 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 262<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/30/03 8:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=990.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Beagle Won't Bark, Shoestring Probe Dead on Arrival </span><hr size=1> I wouldnt write off Beagle just yet but it is true that equipment like this that doesnt work &quot;right first time&quot; useually ends up not working at all<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
