<br>
*&quot;Park orbit&quot; Mars Express and leave it alone for now!<br>
Cut your loses, they're burning fuel and energy for nothing trying to hunt down beagle2.<br>
<br>
*Mars Express was a success 'cause it went the distance at least to Mars orbit no doubt the more birds in orbit around Mars the better future missions to Mars becomes.<br>
<br>
*next time spend the cash and make the lander mission redundant give it a piggyback (two-for-one) on the next Mars Express 2. Russky boosters lifters can handle the load, slip them a couple extra quid to valet your Mars bird<br>
on orbit, drop your landers at least one lander would get safe delivery on the surface if both make it you get double the science.<br>
<br>
Just think, the value of dreaming for tons of kids was mission money well spent. There's probably more Mars Mission posters in kid's rooms than Brittney or Justin or 50cent. <br>
<br>
Well... second thought maybe not.<br>
<br>
Trying is half the fun. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 263<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/31/03 4:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=990.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Suggestions for improving odds </span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>*&quot;Park orbit&quot; Mars Express and leave it alone for now!<br>
Cut your loses, they're burning fuel and energy for nothing trying to hunt down beagle2.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually Im not sure that anybody is specifically &quot;burning fuel&quot; looking for Beagle, If so you are probabally right, at least after Mars Express has passed over a couple of times. after all comms with Odysey was a mission treat, Mars express is the mothership.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>next time spend the cash and make the lander mission redundant give it a piggyback (two-for-one) on the next Mars Express 2. Russky boosters lifters can handle the load, slip them a couple extra quid to valet your Mars bird<br>
on orbit, drop your landers at least one lander would get safe delivery on the surface if both make it you get double the science.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
In principle a sound idea, a cluster of inexpensive landers as opposed to one expensive one. However the sad thing is that the lack of comms means we dont know what is wrong.<br>
<br>
I would be happy to see another mission with 2 (or even half a dozen, they are not very big) Beagle2's on board as long as we are sure that the comms failure was due to bad luck (landing in a crater or next to a huge rock) rather than some sort of internal systems failure. Beagle2's Instrument package is sound for the science we want to do and given that we have already designed and built 1 Beagle2 (the hard bit) I would immagine we could knock out another half dozen for no more than what the first one cost.<br>
<br>
Unfortunatly we dont have enough time to chase mars express with a cluster of fresh Beagle2's so we would also have to build a new mothership complete, though it need not be as sophisticated as mars express unless we want it to be.<br>
<br>
Before doing this we need to establish ( with a reasonable degree of confidence) that the problem is not due to equipment failure otherwise we would just end up with half a dozen duds. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
(After all, how are these things tested, did they take one up to 40,000 feet and drop it out of a plane to see if all the landing systems deplyed correctly?  Not a perfect test I know but probabally better than just reling on computer simulations!)<br>
<br>
<br>
