<br>
Yale-As for transponders my understanding is that although thety are passive insofar as they do not contain a power sourse, they are &quot;Active&quot; insofar as they take enegy from the search beam to retransmit a data stream. ISTM that it would be dificult to make something like this that would work satifactorally from 200 miles away (Tho I may be wrong) with the tiny powers that are available from an orbiter.<br>
<br>
Also, ultimatly, the aim of this exercise is to be able locate a badly damaged otherwise inoperative lander so that we might have at least some possibility of finding out what went wrong. to this end any Tag (passive or otherwise) needs to be passive, independent of the rest of the lander systems, and as simple as possible.<br>
<br>
As for radioisotope tags, I agree that anything that could be seen by an orbiting (Ionising) radiation detector would have to be hot as hell, however, on a cold plannet like Mars, may the *thermal* signiture of a more reasonable ammount of radioisotope be detectable from orbit? A tag of this sort could also serve a dual purpose as an RTG perhaps.<br>
