<br>
I see the system operating something like this:<br>
<br>
A supercapacitor is charged sufficiently (back on Earth) to provide a handful of quite intense radio pulses (&quot;clicks&quot;). An orbiter (or Earth-based) transmitter provides a trigger signal sufficient to activate the pulse. Triangulation would provide location. The &quot;tag&quot; would could be essentially a solid plastic block - capable of surviving a rather nasty landing<br>
As to using the thermal output of an RTG or RTH, would a few hundred watts of broadband infrared noise on a relatively noisy background be visible? I'm not sure. Maybe..<br>
<br>
On the other hand, an RF signal would stand out even at the fraction of a watt level.<br>
<br>
