As a member of Congress, he is assumed (perhaps incorrectly) to have detailed knowledge of the actual current state of these capabilities, making it easy for his reference to them to be taken as evidence of their existence and feasibility. Again, he would certainly be aware of this response. <br>
Indeed, he could not be aware of the concepts themselves without also knowing about the vast array of conspiracy theories that invoke them.<br>
<br>
Yes, the denotation (literal meaning) of &quot;extraterrestrial&quot;  encompasses the definitions listed, but the connotation (common understanding) focuses on the first of the listed definitions, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>originating</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> outside the Earth and its atmosphere. <br>
You left out the second definition of extraterrestrial:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>NOUN: An extraterrestrial being or life form.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
This usage is ambiguous since nouns of identification are very often also employed as adjectives: &quot;American&quot; &quot;Russian&quot; &quot;totalitarian&quot; &quot;activist&quot; etc. <br>
<br>
How often is the term used in reference to human made artifacts? <br>
I ran a <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.google.com/search?hl=en&amp;ie=ISO-8859-1&amp;q=extraterrestrial">google search on &quot;extraterrestrial.&quot;</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> <br>
Not one of the first 100 returns referred in any way to human-made artifacts. <br>
The most widely known example of such usage that I am aware of was Arthur C. Clarke's famous paper &quot;Extraterrestrial Relays.&quot; This was written in 1945, well before &quot;extraterrestrial&quot; became effectively synonymous with aliens. <br>
I seriously doubt that he would use the word in the same context today, lest his article be dismissed as ufo propaganda.  <br>
<br>
Connotation is at least as important as denotation in communication theory, and is certainly so in political and activist rhetoric. It is the aspect that conspiracy theorists have seized upon in citing this bill as a breakthrough in their postulated &quot;curtain of silence&quot; concerning these activities.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 290<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/6/04 7:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=990.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Ok, I apologize for the slur against Martians</span><hr size=1> Or, as our late but unlamented friend PO might say:<br>
